  <main>
    <section class="section">
      <h2>What is the Immune System?</h2>
      <p>The immune system is made up of a complex network of organs, cells, and proteins that fight infection (microbes).</p>
      <h3>Main Parts of the Immune System:</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>White Blood Cells (WBCs):</strong> Made in bone marrow, part of the lymphatic system (T-cells, B-cells, macrophages).</li>
        <li><strong>Organs:</strong> Thymus, spleen, and bone marrow produce and store immune cells.</li>
        <li><strong>Antibodies:</strong> Created by B-cells to target and neutralize invaders.</li>
        <li><strong>Lymphatic System:</strong> Network of lymph nodes and vessels transporting immune cells.</li>
      </ul>
      <h3>Types of Immunity:</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Innate Immunity:</strong> First line of defense, general response.</li>
        <li><strong>Adaptive Immunity:</strong> Specific, memory-based defense against past invaders.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <h2>Autoimmune Diseases</h2>
      <p>Autoimmune diseases occur when the immune system mistakenly attacks the body's own cells, tissues, and organs.</p>
      <h3>Common Types:</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Lupus:</strong> Affects skin, kidneys, heart, joints.</li>
        <li><strong>Graves' Disease:</strong> Attacks the thyroid,
